- FIRST LOOK / AW'98 - 

Hermès, Autumn-Winter 1998-99, coat in camel hair transformable into a cape, vareuse tunic in cashmere with Shetland look, high-necked seamless pullover in cashmere, trousers in wool with shetland look, quick sneakers in leather by PierreHardy.

The “magic of thread” is shown in Margiela’s invention of the boutons à six trous (with six holes), whereby the letter Has suddenly appears like a discreet logo.

- Transformations -
The detachable camelhair lining itself becomes a coat, complete with buttonholes and double buttons which are like-wise detachable. 
- Inside is Outside -
Vents under the arms allow for multiple ways of wearing the garment - wrapped over the shoulders with the sleeves tucked inside, or simply putting your arms through the vents.
Since the underside is just as superb as the outside, you only have to turn the coat inside out to trans-form it into a cape with a bright-colored yoke.
- Semi-structured -
The soft-bodied jacket offers a masculine cut with structured neckline and lapels but naturel, un-padded shoulders.
An ideal ingredient for the layered look. Seen here in camel color with a double row of buttons worn over a knitted, seam-less cashmere jumper.
written from 《LE MONDE D’HERMÈS 1998 VOL. II》
